\section{Introduction}
This learning guide is designed to support Year 9 students in understanding and mastering key topics related to whole numbers, including rounding, place value, and estimation. These fundamental skills form the base for higher-level mathematics and are aligned with the New Zealand Curriculum for Mathematics.

\section{1. Place Value}
\subsection{Theory}
Place value is the value of each digit in a number based on its position. The digits 0–9 can appear in different positions to create different values.

\subsection{Place Value Chart}
\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{|c|c|c|c|c|c|c|}
\hline
Millions & Hundred Thousands & Ten Thousands & Thousands & Hundreds & Tens & Ones \\
\hline
1 & 2 & 3 & 4 & 5 & 6 & 7 \\
\hline
\end{tabular}
\end{center}
This number is: 1,234,567

\subsection{Examples}
\begin{itemize}
    \item In 7,456, the digit 4 is in the hundreds place, so its value is 400.
    \item In 82,301, the digit 8 is in the ten-thousands place, so its value is 80,000.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Practice Activity}
\textbf{Write the value of the underlined digit:}
\begin{enumerate}
    \item 6\underline{5}7
    \item \underline{8}2,190
    \item 2,\underline{0}34
\end{enumerate}

\section{2. Rounding Numbers}
\subsection{Theory}
Rounding means simplifying a number while keeping its value close to what it was. It is useful in estimation and mental math.

\subsection{Rules for Rounding}
\begin{itemize}
    \item Find the place you are rounding to (e.g., nearest ten).
    \item Look at the digit to the right.
    \item If it is 5 or more, round up. If it is 4 or less, round down.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Examples}
\begin{itemize}
    \item Round 367 to the nearest ten: Look at 7 (next to 6). Since 7 \textgreater{}= 5, round up: \textbf{370}
    \item Round 1,234 to the nearest hundred: Look at 3 (next to 2). Since 3 \textless{} 5, round down: \textbf{1,200}
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Practice Activity}
\textbf{Round the following numbers:}
\begin{enumerate}
    \item 648 (to the nearest ten)
    \item 1,357 (to the nearest hundred)
    \item 2,985 (to the nearest thousand)
\end{enumerate}

\section{3. Estimating}
\subsection{Theory}
Estimation is used to make quick calculations by rounding numbers first. It is especially helpful when an exact answer is not needed.

\subsection{Examples}
\begin{itemize}
    \item Estimate 398 + 246: Round to 400 + 250 = \textbf{650}
    \item Estimate 1,230 - 489: Round to 1,200 - 500 = \textbf{700}
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Practice Activity}
\textbf{Estimate the following:}
\begin{enumerate}
    \item 894 + 1,102
    \item 2,375 - 1,148
    \item 3,012 + 4,987
\end{enumerate}

\newpage

\section{Knowledge and Skills Assessment}
\subsection*{Instructions:} Answer the questions below. Show all your working where possible.

\begin{enumerate}
    \item Write the place value of the underlined digits:
    \begin{itemize}
        \item 1,\underline{2}36
        \item 7\underline{5}1
    \end{itemize}
    \item Round the following numbers:
    \begin{itemize}
        \item 3,986 (nearest ten)
        \item 12,345 (nearest hundred)
        \item 6,492 (nearest thousand)
    \end{itemize}
    \item Estimate the following:
    \begin{itemize}
        \item 3,894 + 2,143
        \item 7,823 - 3,445
        \item 5,378 + 6,921
    \end{itemize}
\end{enumerate}

\subsection*{Optional Challenge:}
Explain in your own words: Why is estimation important in real life?

